Couldn’t let this day end without a shoutout to my ride or die, Daniel Ryan. 

He may have rolled up the car window on my foot this morning but he made up for it by keeping us alive in the few near-accidents we had on the road up to Koke’e 🙈. 

PSA—don’t stop in the middle of the road (especially if cars are right behind you). Pull over to the side of the road to take photos of that waterfall or rainbow.

Gracias amor for your superb driving skills (and for listening to me when I nag you to keep your verbal warnings on the friendlier side 🫣🤭😘). And yes, Kaua’i needs the cheeky road safety signs that Australia has. #StopReviveSurvive

#KauaiLife #Kauai #Thankful #SoloTuYYo #Thanksgiving2022 📸 @ashfabhawaii

Three weeks in beautiful Australia. What a wonderfully wild 10th birthday adventure for Kahlo. We can’t wait to return and explore more!

It all seems like a lifetime ago as the days of this season blur together at lightning speed. Take me back to daily dream baths, rainforest treks, and every meal al fresco. To the sweetness of a slow and simple life.

In case you’re considering a trip to lovely land down under, I’ll be sharing more of our itinerary in my Stories today (and they’ll be added to the Destinations Highlight on my profile).

Life is art and art is life. Awakening by @rebeccalouiselaw now showing through September 2023 @honolulumuseum 🌸. Mu’umu’u Month day five in Jacqueline’s of Hawaii and Melibea in Nikky.

When I read about Awakening in @hanahoumag it said that some people were brought to tears upon their first visit. Sure enough, this immersive installation truly took my breath away as a million plus flowers cascaded around us. Sheer delight spread across Meli’s face and throughout her entire body—sparkles in her eyes, a spring in her step. Pure magic.

If you find yourself on Oahu this year be sure to spend some time wandering through Law’s masterpiece. Better yet, follow her wishes and keep your camera tucked away (until the designated area) to simply soak in the experience. Open your eyes and see what surfaces, wake up!

Where there’s a visionboard, there’s a way. Mu’umu’u Month day 14 in Hawaiian Togs with Meli and Ru in Kole Kole.

One of my favorite ways to start the year is the visionboarding workshop with @lei.ofkauai ✨. In addition to the reflection and visualization pieces, I find that sharing our aspirations aloud is so incredibly powerful. Bria takes it to the next level and after each wahine’s turn everyone writes her a little love note—some words of encouragement for those rainy days.

My word for 2023 is intention. In this wild season of raising our four children and growing our business I want to be even more intentional with my time, money, and energy. I used to tell myself to slow down but I’ve come to realize that’s not what I want at all. This pace is the pace for me because as busy as I am, I can always bring myself back to the “why” behind everything I choose to do. It’s a simple practice that makes all the difference.

Today marks what would’ve been my Lolo’s 83rd birthday. I sure wish he was down here to celebrate with, he would’ve loved our party of six. I wish our keiki could’ve met the person who meant and gave the world to me.

Most of you probably don’t know that instead of a mother and father, I was raised by my grandfather. Truth be told, I was raised by many but Lolo was something special. He was hardworking, generous, and the living definition of unconditional love. I aspire to honor these qualities of his in all that I do.

And one day, I hope our keiki realize that the sense of endless possibility we’ve cultivated in them began with him. 

#TheseWildDays #Kauai #Ohana #ChildhoodUnplugged #OptOutside #HappyBirthdayLolo #HauoliLaHanau #MaligayangBati

A hui hou Island of Hawai’i! My recap of our recent island hopping adventure is live on le blog. Follow the link in my profile to learn more about where we stayed, played, and ate. In the meanwhile, here are three observations I made after a week in the Hilo and Puna moku:

1. There is a distinct emphasis on Hawaiian language and culture nearly everywhere you go. I highly recommend visiting this island to proactively immerse yourself in these important facets of Hawaiian life. 

2. Prepare yourself for a lot of driving time. It wasn’t formerly referred to as the Big Island for no reason! Unless you’re staying in Volcanoes National Park or the nearby Volcano Village, you’re at least 45 minutes away (and you’ll want to visit more than once to get the full experience).

3. This Ōlelo no’eau said it best:
Hilo i ka ua kinakinai, 
ka ua mao ‘ole.
Hilo of the constant rain,
where it never clears up.
Embrace the rain and the beauty it adds to this wild side of Hawai’i. Pack accordingly and don’t let the weather stop you from adventuring (within reason of course).

#TheseWildDays #IslandOfHawaii #BigIsland #HawaiiIsland #Hilo #Pāhoa #Puna #OptOutside #WeAreAllAdventurers #ShotOniPhone #Reels #ChildhoodUnplugged #AnywhereAloha

Breakfast for six. 

I recently received our full galleries of photographs from Oz Farm 2022 a la @breewalkerphotography — they reminded me of how much I love our slow pace of life on the road. We are both enamored with and curious about life in foreign places—about how different it can look, sound, and feel. Thus in our travels we strive for life experiences, not bucket list destinations.

When you visit a place what are the things you like to notice most? I always pay attention to how people share meals. I observe how families, friends, and lovers engage with each other at the table. I admire how in certain places people are so present with one another, it’s a beautiful thing to witness but even better to experience ✨.

At the close of yet another adventure, I am feeling extra thankful to have a partner who is fully committed to living the life of our dreams together. There’s an ebb and flow to this balancing act, and I am loving this season of divide and conquer. In a big family like ours, it’s refreshing to get one-on-one or even two-and-one time together. It feels like such a luxury to devote my full presence to anything less than the six of us!

Like everything else in life, this has to be arranged with intention. And so here we are, making the most of every moment together or apart. Because in this season we are wide open and generous with making space for each other’s solo time. Small daily sacrifices transform into shared victories. Love is a practice, lean into it and see for yourself.

Traveling with keiki is no easy feat but here are some tips to help make it go smoother!

1. Prepare healthy snacks for the airport and airplane ride. Fruit, nuts, charcuterie-type fixings. We also pre-order our meals from @alaskaair — doing this offers us more options and the keiki know what to expect.

2. At eight and ten, our boys pack their own @walkerfamilygoods backpacks but we keep things simple for our girls (ages two and five). They select a favorite light blanket, stuffed animal/doll, and art activity. For longer flights, I also surprise them with something small like a sticker book.

3. Unless we are flying inter-island, we always put the keiki in socks and comfortable shoes. It’s one less thing to take up space in their luggage, plus they can slip off their shoes while keeping their feet warm on the flight.

4. Plan to spend some extra time cruising around the airport. No one likes rushing with keiki and this way they get to expend their extra energy. Checkout the walking escalators, observe the floor to ceiling views from different gates, etc.

5. As with most things, you’ll be amazed at how much even a toddler can do independently at the airport. And even if they’re not quite tall enough—they can help get their items on the security screening belt, help fill their water bottle, walk to their seat on the plane, and so on.

6. The thing about having solid routines at home is that you can try those same steps in a variety of environments. Nap time for Ru looks quite similar whether it’s at home (on her bed) or on an airplane (preferably next to us but sometimes on top of us). We read a book, sing a song, then snuggle.

This week in the news there was a story about four children (ages 13, 9, 4 and 11 months) who were lost for 40 days in the Amazon jungle after their small plane crashed. One article described how the children could climb and literally run through the trees.

Learning more about their experience made me reflect on the childhood you are helping shape for our keiki—all of the freedom and independence you facilitate for them to confidently adventure in the wild. Their little minds are always trying to keep up with your problem solving exercises, while their bare feet are always a few steps behind yours. It’s truly a gift to watch this unfold. 

From building a fire to exploring through storms, using patience as a strategy to taking calculated risks—you’ve shown them how to live their lives outside of four walls. And above all, I love how you’ve taught them to respect instead of fear the whole world beyond our doorstep.

Sharing is caring (and a lifelong skill).

The heaviness of the past week is felt throughout the Hawaiian islands and beyond. In our home there are a lot of questions about what happened, why it happened, and how we can help. Here on Kaua’i the entire island is rallying together to support the survivors as they navigate unimaginable loss. 

Beyond shipping supplies and fundraising, we are amplifying the following messages:

1. Cancel your vacation to West Maui. The community needs time to grieve, heal, and rebuild. 

2. Send support however you are able to. @kennareed has a running list of families you can donate to directly. You can also check out @hawaiicommunityfoundation @mauifoodbank @mauihumanesociety 

3. Most local businesses here in Hawai’i (including @thefreshshave 🤍) have initiated fundraisers for various relief efforts on Maui. @hawaiimomblog has even compiled a list of these opportunities! Even if you cannot participate yourself, go ahead and spread the word so others can. 

#MauiStrong

Parenting. The most exhausting yet soul-filling work there is. The glimmers of hope were few and far between last week but they appeared just when we needed them the most.

The first two slides are poems written by Tamayo and Melibea for a contest at their school. The theme was “I am hopeful because…” As a fourth grader, Mayo began by listing problems he’s observed and discussing what his role could be in helping solve them. As a kindergartner, Meli reflected on things that make her feel hopeful and happy.

Slides three and four are from a spontaneous after school mission to the mountains. The air is always so healing up there, that golden hour is pure magic. Slides five and six are Neruda’s self-portrait and a peek at Kahlo’s dance performance. Raising tiny humans isn’t always this beautiful—but when it is, it deserves to be celebrated.

During the busy season that defines December I find joy in the art of noticing. It slows me down. Taking pauses between tasks to simply observe what they notice. I love wondering about what they’re thinking, as they move through their day with mysteriously pure intentions.

One of the raddest yet most difficult things to do as a parent is to sit back and watch a tiny human’s life unfold. To not interrupt their daily rhythms—their explorations of curiosity and experiences of struggle. It’s a practice we dive into from every child’s birth, and it truly does take practice (plus loads of patience).

But in the end it’s so worth it because it allows each of them to discover how to interact with the world, in a very peaceful and natural way. It instills a sense of confidence within them that is truly self driven. My goodness, it’s a wondrous process to witness.
